  "prompt": "How can I find wps pin on my galaxy S5 connected wifi?",
  "response": "Finding the WPS (Wi-Fi Protected Setup) PIN on your Galaxy S5 or any connected Wi-Fi network is not something that can be directly done through the device itself. The WPS PIN is typically generated by the router and is used to allow devices to connect to the Wi-Fi network without needing to enter the password.\n\nHere are some steps you can take to find or use the WPS PIN:\n\n### 1. **Check the Router:**\n   - The WPS PIN is usually found on a label on the back or bottom of your Wi-Fi router. It may be labeled as \"WPS PIN\" or \"PIN.\"\n   - If you have access to the router's admin interface, you can log in and check the WPS settings to find the PIN.\n\n### 2. **Use the WPS Button:**\n   - If your router has a WPS button, you can use it to connect your Galaxy S5 to the Wi-Fi network without needing the PIN.\n   - On your Galaxy S5, go to **Settings > Wi-Fi**.\n   - Tap on the three-dot menu or the \"Advanced\" option.\n   - Select \"WPS Push Button\" or \"WPS PIN Entry\" depending on your router's setup.\n   - Press the WPS button on your router within the specified time (usually 2 minutes).\n\n### 3. **Router Admin Interface:**\n   - Access your router's admin interface by entering its IP address (commonly 192.168.1.1 or 192.168.0.1) in a web browser.\n   - Log in with your admin username and password (often found on the router label).\n   - Navigate to the WPS settings section to find or generate the WPS PIN.\n\n### 4. **Contact Your ISP:**\n   - If you cannot find the WPS PIN and do not have access to the router's admin interface, you may need to contact your Internet Service Provider (ISP) for assistance.\n\n### Important Notes:\n- **Security:** WPS is considered less secure than other methods of connecting to Wi-Fi because the PIN can be brute-forced by attackers. It is recommended to disable WPS on your router if you are not actively using it.\n- **Compatibility:** Not all routers or devices support WPS. Ensure that both your router and Galaxy S5 support WPS before attempting to use this method.\n\nIf you are trying to recover or find the Wi-Fi password itself (not the WPS PIN), you can use methods like checking it on a connected device, accessing the router's admin interface, or using third-party apps (root access may be required).",
  "temperature": 1.0,
